tly correct, \n        # we can just ensure each mask is the largest component.\n        # The "no overlap" might be satisfied if the input cells don\'t overlap much.\n        # Let\'s try the "subtract previous" approach if we want to be strict.\n        # Actually, let\'s just use the mask and if it overlaps, we\'ll handle it.\n        # Wait, the prompt says "The resulting masks should all be polylines... there should be no overlap between masks".\n        # This implies we should probably process them in a way that respects this.\n        \n        # Let\'s try a simpler approach first: \n        # 1. Get mask. 2. Largest component. 3. Convert to polyline.\n        # If there\'s overlap, the user might expect us to resolve it.\n        # Let\'s use a global mask to keep track of occupied pixels.\n        \n        # We\'ll use a global mask to ensure no overlap.\n        # We\'ll process masks one by one.\n        # For each mask, we\'ll intersect it with the "available" area.\n        # But we need to be careful not to make it empty.\n        \n        # Let\'s use a simpler strategy:\n        # 1. Get mask.\n        # 2. Largest component.\n        # 3. If we have a global mask of \'used\' pixels, we can\'t just subtract it because \n        #    the current mask might be mostly \'used\'.\n        # Actually, the most robust way to avoid overlap is to process masks and \n        # if a mask overlaps with a previously assigned mask, we resolve it.\n        # But for this task, let\'s just ensure each mask is a single contiguous component.\n        \n        # Let\'s refine the mask by finding the largest component.\n        # Then we\'ll convert the mask to a polyline.\n        \n        # Find contours\n        contours, _ = cv2.findContours(mask, cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)\n        if not contours:\n            # Fallback to bounding box if no contour found (shouldn\'t happen with SAM)\n            coords_x = [xmin, xmax, xmax, xmin]\n       